How MCP Connector Works (AccuWeather)
MCP connectors are added by editing the claude_desktop_config.json file.

Config file location:
Windows: %APPDATA%\Claude\claude_desktop_config.json
Mac: ~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json
What the JSON looks like:
json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "accuweather": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-accuweather"],
      "env": {
        "ACCUWEATHER_API_KEY": "your_api_key_here"
      }
    }
  }
}
Steps I followed:
Opened claude_desktop_config.json
Added the AccuWeather server config
Added API key in the env section
Restarted Claude Desktop
Claude can now answer weather questions using real AccuWeather data ✅
What is MCP Architecture
Claude Desktop (Host)
      ↓
MCP Client (built into Claude Desktop)
      ↓
MCP Server (AccuWeather / Local Server)
      ↓
External Tool / API / Data
Key Concepts Learned
MCP Host → Claude Desktop (the app)
MCP Client → built into the host, manages connections
MCP Server → the bridge between Claude and external tools
Tools → functions Claude can call (get_weather, add_expense etc.)
Resources → data Claude can read
JSON config → how you tell Claude Desktop which servers to connect
